Exercise-1

Compute and plot the population size over the first 50 generations for r = 0.5, 2.8, 3.3.

library(deSolve)
#x0 is the initial value of the population. xn is the measure of population growth in nth generation. r is the growth rate.
x0 <- rep(0.1,3)
r <- c(0.5,2.8,3.3) # growth rate
xi <- matrix(data=NA,nrow=50,ncol=3) #defining xn
xi[1,] <- x0
xn <- x0
for(i in 2:50){ 
xi[i,] <- xn*(1-xn)*r 
xn <- xi[i,]
}

What did you notice with different values of r? Can you give a heuristic explanation for the behaviour you observe?

As the generations progress, the growth rate r has significant effect on population growth(or the size of the population). In the plot below, we can see that the size of of the population tends towards zero when r < 1. It increases to reach its maximum, oscillates and stabilizes to steady state for r =2.8. For r = 3.3, it oscillates and settles down into unstable steady state.

{plot(xi[,1],
     type = "l",
     col = "black", 
     ylim =c(0,1), 
     xlab = "Number of Generations", 
     ylab = "Size of the population")
  lines(xi[,2],col="orange")
  lines(xi[,3],col="blue")}

Exercise-2

Implement the Forward Euler algorithm and compute the solution to the following initial value problem for t [0, 5], for the following step sizes: h = 0.1, 0.01, 0.001.

euler <- function(f, x0, tmax, h) {
    t0 <- 0
    x<-array(NA, dim = c(tmax/h+1,2))
    t <- seq(0,tmax,h)
    x[,1]<-t
    x[1,2]<-x0
    for(i in 2:((tmax/h)+1)) {
      x[i,2]<-x[i-1,2]+h*x[i-1,2]
       }
     
    return(data.frame(x = x, t = t))
}
e1 = euler(f=function(x){return(x)},x0 = 1,tmax = 5,h=0.1)
e2 = e = euler(f=function(x){return(x)},x0 = 1,tmax = 5,h=0.01)
e3 = e = euler(f=function(x){return(x)},x0 = 1,tmax = 5,h=0.001)

Plot these solution overlaid with the function x(t) = exp(t). What do you observe? Is this what you would expect?Why or why not?

In the plot below, as we would expect, we can see that dx/dt tends towards e^x as h goes to zero.

{plot(e1$t,e1$x.2,type = "l", col = "black",xlab = "t", ylab = "dx/dt")
lines(e2$t,e2$x.2, type = "l", col = "orange")
lines(e3$t,e3$x.2,type = "l", col = "blue")
lines(e1$x.2,exp(e1$x.2),type="l",col= "red")}

Exercise -3 FitzHugh Nagumo Model

Part-1 Compute the solution to this system until t = 400 for v(0) = 1, w(0) = 0.1, I = 0.5 (a step size of 0.01 should suffice).

I <- 0.5
a <- 0.7
b <- 0.8
e <- 0.08
tmax <- 400
h <- 0.01
t <- seq(0,tmax,h)
out <- array(NA, dim = c(tmax/h+1, 3))
out[,1] <- t
out[1,2] <- 1
out[1,3] <- 0.1
for(i in 2:((tmax/h)+1)) {
     out[i,2] <- out[i-1,2]+h*(out[i-1,2]-((out[i-1,2]^3)/3)-out[i-1,3]+I)
     out[i,3] <- out[i-1,3]+h*(e*(out[i-1,2]+a-b*out[i-1,3]))
}

Plot the variable v against t you should see oscillations.

plot(x = out[,1], y = out[,2], type = "l", xlab = "t", ylab = "v")

plot(x = out[,2], y = out[,3], type = "l", xlab = "v", ylab = "w")

Exercise-3(Part-2)

Plot v against w, that is, look at the trajectory in phase space. Notice that after a small transient, the trajectory stays on a loop in phase space. This is a special type of attractor called a limit cycle. Calculate the v-nullcline and w-nullcline and graph these on the same plot as your trajectory.

library(phaseR)
## -------------------------------------------------------------------------------
## phaseR: Phase plane analysis of one- and two-dimensional autonomous ODE systems
## -------------------------------------------------------------------------------
## 
## v.2.1: For an overview of the package's functionality enter: ?phaseR
## 
## For news on the latest updates enter: news(package = "phaseR")
FHN <- function(t, y, parameters) {
  I_0 <- parameters
  e<- 0.08
  b<-0.8
  a<-0.7
  dy <- numeric(2)
  dy[1] <- 2 *  ( y[1] - 1/3 * y[1]^3 - y[2]) + I_0
  dy[2] <- e*(y[1] + a - b*(y[2]))   
  return(list(dy))
}
phasePlot <- function(FHN, I_0=0.5){
  FHN.flowField  <- flowField(FHN, xlim = c(-3, 3), 
                              ylim = c(-3, 3),
                              xlab="v", ylab="w",
                              main=paste0("I=", I_0),
                              parameters = I_0, 
                              points = 15, add = FALSE)  
  FHN.nullclines <- nullclines(FHN, xlim = c(-3, 3), 
                               ylim = c(-3, 3),
                               parameters = I_0, 
                               points = 400)  
  y0 <- c(1, 0.1)
  FHN.trajectory <- trajectory(FHN, y0 = y0, tlim = c(0,400), 
                               parameters = I_0)
}

phasePlot(FHN, I_0 = 0.5)

Exercise-3(part-6) Write a for loop to calculate the steady-state values (v,w) and its stability for values of I ranging between 0 and 0.5.

tmax = 400
h = 0.01
a = 0.7
b = 0.8
e = 0.08
X <-array(data = NA, dim =c(51,5))
I <-seq(0,0.5,0.01)
for(j in seq(1,51)){
  X[j,1] <- I[j]
  X[j,2] <-polyroot(z =c((b*I[j]-a), (b-1), 0,-b/3))[2]
  X[j,3] <- (X[j,2]+a)/b
  X[j,4:5] <-eigen(x =matrix(data =c(1-X[j,2]^2, e, -1,-e*b), nrow = 2, ncol = 2))$values
}

Graph v against I and plot in blue where v is stable and red where v is unstable.

{plot(x = I, y = X[,2], type = "l", col = "black", xlab = "I", ylab = "V", lwd = 2)
lines(x = I[which(Re(X[,4])>0)], y = X[which(Re(X[,4])>0),2], col = "blue", lwd = 2)
lines(x = I[which(Re(X[,4])<0)], y = X[which(Re(X[,4])<0),2], col = "orange", lwd = 2)}
